Environment-Climate: For a European New Deal
BRUSSELS – In Brussels, as in other European capitals, the "Green New Deal" is on everyone's lips, echoing the visionary economic program launched by President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1933.
But this time, it is about the environment and climate.
And Europe is the continent where we can and must act.
The European Union's commitment on these issues is not new: we have had a joint program since 1972.
Later in 2005, the EU established the first emissions trading system, which remains the world's largest carbon market.
And in 2015, the EU played a driving role in negotiating the Paris Agreement, committing to reduce its own greenhouse gas emissions by 40% (baseline: 1990 levels).
But these measures, despite their importance, are not sufficient to meet the challenges faced by today's world.
Rising temperatures could lead to the complete disappearance of Arctic sea ice by 2050.
Bees and many other insects are dying out, as microplastic pollution is omnipresent in our environment.
And the number of people suffering from respiratory diseases is increasing as air pollution worsens.
We nevertheless have reasons to remain optimistic.
Let's look at these people, growing in number day by day, ready to act to question their ways of life. Like these students and entire families marching into the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursday!
Companies, too, are committing themselves, seeing the unparalleled economic potential of a green economy.
But it is the politicians and political leaders, at both the national and European levels, who too often lack ambition.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Let's seize it!
And let us make a green Europe our top political priority for the years to come, focused on three key areas.
Firstly, Europe must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit global warming to 1.5°C, we have no choice: the EU's net carbon dioxide emissions must be reduced to zero by mid-century.
Together, we can massively invest in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings, and renewable energies, as well as in key technologies such as hydrogen batteries, new generations of solar panels, and green chemistry.
Together, we must also impose strict CO2 emission limits on new passenger cars, public transportation, as well as maritime and air commercial transport.
And, by working closely with our automobile industry, we can make Europe the leading continent for electric vehicles by 2030.
Secondly, Europe must play a leading role in the responsible use of resources and become a true circular economy that minimizes waste.
Each year, 8 billion tonnes of materials are converted into energy or products within the European Union.
But only 0.6 billion tons come from recycling.
We must do much better, which will require us to focus on four areas: food waste and bioeconomy, textiles, construction, and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let us start working today, for example, by launching an European initiative to combat the programmed obsolescence of household appliances and electronic devices, and by abolishing plastics from our value chains.
Thirdly, we must do much more to protect biodiversity.
According to the WWF, wild species populations have decreased by about 60% worldwide since 1970.
The United Nations biodiversity conference, which will be held in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Once again, the EU must set the example.
We must strengthen EU legislation on species protection and put forward an ambitious plan for the blue economy and the preservation of our seas.
We must also launch a real debate with our farmers (not against them!) on revising our standards and modernizing the common agricultural policy to support this green transition.
But these colossal projects that await us, we will not be able to accomplish them if it is always the same people — and those most vulnerable — who are asked to bear their costs.
All measures under consideration must therefore first and foremost be designed to minimize social costs.
And in parallel, we must start working today with our partners for international cooperation, fighting against unfair competition.
For it serves no purpose to have strict European rules on pesticides or forest management if our imported food and timber are produced without respecting sustainability criteria.
These three projects could become the pillars of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the EU's new political cycle.
For we are in a state of acute ecological debt, and it would be more than justified for the Stability and Growth Pact, which applies to the public finances of member states, to have an equivalent for the goals of a green Europe!
To achieve its goals, this Sustainability Pact will require coordinated action across all areas: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU should not fear using its regulatory powers; for example, expanding the scope of legislation on eco-design and "extended producer responsibility" for products placed on the market could significantly stimulate environmental innovation.
Massive investments will also be necessary.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional 180 billion euros in investments each year to meet its commitments under the Paris Agreement.
It is an achievable goal.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral funder focused on climate.
And the new EU budget and its investment plan, making the best use of private sector investments, could further enhance the Union's capacity to act.
The financial sector will have to play a fundamental role: through the disclosure of climate-related financial information, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as the Norwegian Sovereign Wealth Fund and BlackRock, to adopt a long-term perspective and avoid what Bank of England Governor Mark Carney called the "tragedy of the horizon."
Finally, although some member states may view it as a risky project, we must have a debate on taxation, as well as on subsidies applicable to fossil fuels. In short, on the integration of sustainability into public spending.
Behind these projects and initiatives, the key lies in the method. For this "Green New Deal" to bear fruit, we must set ambitious goals and define "missions" with both short- and long-term horizons that truly resonate with society.
Together with the Member States and the European Parliament, we will need to determine a common roadmap and conduct in-depth discussions, just as we do with our regions, cities, businesses, trade unions, and civil society.
All of this cannot be done overnight.
But we can no longer close our eyes and hold our breath to escape the reality of our environment.
It is already very late to launch a European "Green New Deal." But it is not too late.
Let's not miss this new opportunity!
